{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17608740","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17608740"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:36:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:36:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16014"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16014","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16014"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8705"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63504"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8705","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8705"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16014"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48958"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1891"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7567"},{"type":"tags","id":"8130"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20825"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20828"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63504","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/63504"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ECleft lip and palate are common congenital facial anomalies that occur during embryonic development. Different types of clefts can affect various anatomical structures to different degrees.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes a complete unilateral cleft lip and primary palate?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cleft extending through lip and alveolus to incisive foramen","Bilateral cleft of lip and primary palate","Cleft of the lip only","Cleft of the secondary palate only","Cleft extending from lip to soft palate"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ecomplete unilateral cleft extending through lip and alveolus to incisive foramen\u003C/strong\u003E correctly describes a complete unilateral cleft lip and primary palate. This occurs due to failure of fusion between the medial nasal process and maxillary process during weeks 4-12 of embryonic development.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECleft of the lip only\u003C/strong\u003E represents an incomplete cleft lip that does not extend into the alveolus\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECleft of the secondary palate only\u003C/strong\u003E involves structures posterior to the incisive foramen and is embryologically distinct\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECleft extending from lip to soft palate\u003C/strong\u003E describes a complete unilateral cleft lip and palate involving both primary and secondary palate\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBilateral cleft of lip and primary palate\u003C/strong\u003E involves both sides of the face rather than a single side\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incisive foramen serves as an important anatomical landmark dividing the primary palate (anterior) from the secondary palate (posterior).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Complete unilateral cleft lip and palate extends through the lip, alveolus, and primary palate up to the incisive foramen","Cleft lip and palate occurs due to failure of fusion of embryonic facial processes during weeks 4-12 of development"],"references":["Vyas T, Gupta P, Kumar S, Gupta R, Gupta T, Singh HP. Cleft of lip and palate: A review. J Family Med Prim Care. 2020 Jun 30;9(6):2621-2625. doi: 10.4103/jfmpc.jfmpc_472_20. PMID: 32984097; PMCID: PMC7491837","Pang J, Broyles J, Redett R. Cleft lip and palate. Eplasty. 2013;13:ic25. Epub 2013 Jan 30. PMID: 23409216; PMCID: PMC3567612","Arulkumaran, S., Ledger, W., Denny, L., \u0026 Doumouchtsis, S. (Eds.). (2019). Oxford Textbook of Obstetrics and Gynaecology. Oxford University Press","Singh, V. (2022). Textbook of clinical embryology, -E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48958"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16014"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48958","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/48958"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-21T00:52:57+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-21T00:53:36+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8705"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63504"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"d